black lab w advanced melanoma time to put to sleep our lab was diagnosed with melanoma in march this year the vet gave him months he's still with us today the last couple days though he started refusing his canned food although he eats hard dry food normally he appears to have slowed down he doesn't seem very happy although he does not appear to be in physical pain but he has trouble drinking water now too is this too much discomfort that tells us putting him to sleep asap is a good idea we don't want him to suffer needlessly thanks for any advice it's always a hard decision to put an animal to sleep we just put our year old cocker spaniel to sleep this past spring we were waiting for a sure sign that it was the right time it came a couple of days after she started sleeping a lot she stopped eating completely and hardly ever drank this was totally unlike her because she was usually a peppy dog who was always hungry you know your dog the best and he'll give you a sign when the time is right trust your intuition when it comes to it good luck Fecal incontinence Similarities between the Bible and the Qur'an Dog The Amazing Race Garfield Humphrey Bogart Pitaten Guinea pig Malignant melanoma Social rule Theory of conduct Traumatic incident reduction Kodocha Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Psoriasis Wild at Heart (Buffy episode) Stomach cancer Marathon (sport) The Catcher in the Rye Insomnia Kosher foods Kitchen Manos: The Hands of Fate Dog training Fancy rat Piccolo Junior Saga Cat Urinary incontinence Rocko's Modern Life Knots Landing Fasting Sleeping Murder Ferret Cancer Equine conformation 2005 trial of Michael Jackson Asterix and the Laurel Wreath Happiness Caffeine English Cocker Spaniel Whaling Spaniel Chinese New Year W.I.T.C.H. Tooth enamel Dehydration Apollo 8 Mixed-breed dog Lisa the Vegetarian Alcoholics Anonymous Prostate cancer Shaggy dog story Taboo food and drink Cavalier King Charles Spaniel 2000 Australian Grand Prix The Life and Times of Juniper Lee Tlingit Bob a